entry.title: trusted_vault: return the epoch when adding a domain member.
entry.content:
The code currently assumes that, when creating a security domain,

`RegisterDeviceWithoutKeys` is used. The callback to that function

is passed a `TrustedVaultKeyAndVersion` which includes the epoch of the

new security domain (which the server generates).



But, in that context, the key of the `TrustedVaultKeyAndVersion` must be

the all-zeros key, so the only meaningful value _is_ the epoch.



`RegisterAuthenticationFactor` doesn't return the epoch so can only be

used to add a member to an existing security domain where the epoch is

known. But the hw_protected security domain never uses the all-zero key

and thus needs to use `RegisterAuthenticationFactor` to create a

security domain.



Thus the `RegisterAuthenticationFactorCallback` needs an `int` parameter

to communicate the epoch. But then it's essentially the same as the

callback to `RegisterDeviceWithoutKeys`, and so they can be unified.

accurately from the GPU process so remove the base::Feature check

entry.title: [Signin][Android] Fix restore metric & use bool for "recorded" status
entry.content:
In https://crrev.com/c/5191994, the magic value of the enum value

RestoreStatus.RESTORE_STATUS_RECORDED has been changed. Since it was

saved to prefs, and used to prevent additional histogram recording.



It has broken the restore metrics Android.RestoreResult, since devices

having old prefs and with the status already recorded consider that

the restore status has not been recorded yet, and records the status

histogram again.



This CL uses a new value for the sign-in timed out metric since the old one is polluted, and introduces a boolean pref used to indicate whether

the restore status has been recorded, to limit similar accident in the future.

entry.title: [anchor] Set AnchorScope during inset/sizing property application
entry.content:
The behavior of anchor queries depends on which property we're currently

applying: for example, anchor() queries are only valid in inset

properties, and anchor-size() queries are only valid in sizing

properties [1][2]. Therefore, AnchorEvaluators have a current mode

which is set by placing an AnchorScope object on the stack.



This CL ensures that we have the necessary AnchorScope object

on the stack during Foo::ApplyValue. This makes it possible to

evaluate anchor queries in those properties computed-value time,

once the real AnchorEvaluator (AnchorEvaluatorImpl) is propagated

from layout into UpdateStyleForOutOfFlow (future CL).



[1] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-anchor-position-1/#anchor-valid

[2] https://drafts.csswg.org/css-anchor-position-1/#anchor-size-valid

The use here is essentially the same as that described in [1]. It is a

little more indirect as the ClientSharedImage here can be created via

the GpuBacking to getting it via the ClientSharedImage as we did in

[1]. NOTE: Like in [1], we temporarily add an equality CHECK to

validate the conversion. However, it must be slightly relaxed as

unittests broadly hit this code with GpuBacking instances on which they

entry.title: NavigationPredictor: Prune anchor data for removed elements
entry.content:
NavigationPredictor stores information about anchor elements in the

page and retains this information for the lifetime of the page. This

is a problem for long lived pages which update themselves with new

links. For example, on https://source.chromium.org/ , switching the

file being viewed is a same document navigation and the code view has

many cross reference links. We currently keep accumulating anchor data

for anchors that are no longer in the document. This can lead to

significant wasted memory.



We now have the renderer notify the browser of anchors that have been

removed, so that the browser can prune information about these

anchors. It still retains the anchor id in order for it to tell if an

anchor is reinserted into the document so it doesn't treat it as a new

anchor.



Note that between the time of the renderer computing the metrics for

an anchor and the update being sent to the browser, the anchor could

be removed from the document (and then possibly reinserted). Before

sending the buffered updates, we do a pass over them to remove stale

updates. We wait until this point in order to avoid having bookkeeping

on hot code paths. Similarly, we elide reports of insertions if they're

removed before reporting and removals which are followed by a

reinsertion.



We also now only consider insertions of elements when they are

connected to a document. This simplifies the removal tracking logic.

Anchors that aren't connected would have been ignored later on anyway.

entry.title: Replace WebElement::Form() call by form_util::GetOwningForm().
entry.content:
The WebFormElement used in FormCache::ClearSectionWithElement is used

in a single place, namely as an argument to

form_util::GetAutofillableFormControlElements. That, in turn, calls

GetFormControlElements, which is shadow DOM aware. Therefore the

WebFormElement should also be obtained by using GetOwningForm.



Otherwise, the following scenario would not yield the correct

autofillable form control elements:

- Element is an unassociated form control element inside shadow DOM.

- The shadow host is contained inside a form.



Here the right form to return is the form owning the shadow host. This

is what GetOwningForm does.

entry.title: MojoLPM: introduce MojoLPMGenerator
entry.content:
MojoLPMGenerator aims at simplifying MojoLPM usage by generating some of

the redundant and not interesting bits from a fuzzer developer POV.



This CL introduces multiple things:

1. A new script that is capable of generating both the `.proto` and

corresponding C++ code for generating a MojoLPM fuzzer based on a mojo

interface. The C++ part is simply a `.h` file containing a class that

developer should inherit from in order to remove some of the MojoLPM

boilerplate. See crrev.com/c/5206110 for an example of how this works.

2. A new GN template that helps using this generator. This new template

provides all the existing features of `mojolpm_fuzzer_test`, including

seed corpus handling.



From a fuzzer developer POV, the structure of the proto file doesn't

matter, except if using a seed corpus. In that case, this doesn't change

much from the existing way MojoLPM works, since the internal structure

must be known to the developer in order to be able to write corpus

files.



Fuzzer developer would only need to override the "new" method for the

mojom interface they wish to fuzz. Even if the mojo interface was to

change, this bit will remain, independently of the mojo interface

structure.

entry.title: Implement DOM Clobbering use counters
entry.content:
This change introduces new UseCounters to understand the usage of

patterns that lead to DOM Clobbering. Four new counters are implemented:



- kDOMClobberedShadowedDocumentPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedNotShadowedDocumentPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedShadowedFormPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedNotShadowedFormPropertyAccessed



First two are meant to count usage of DOM Clobbering on document. For

example: would create a new property: document.abc.

We distinguish whether this property name would shadow an existing

property or not.



The latter two count usage of DOM Clobbering on forms. Similarly to

document, we also distinguish between shadowed and non-shadowed

properties.



These UseCounters will help make a decision on whether we can disable

some flavors of DOM Clobbering by default.



Also this CL changes the name of existing counter:

kDOMClobberedVariableAccessed -> kDOMClobberedWindowPropertyAccessed



to make it more consistent with the other counters.
